Silhouette method

# Define a function to calculate average silhouette for k
avg_sil <- function(k, scaled_data) {
  pam.res <- pam(scaled_data, k = k)
  ss <- silhouette(pam.res$clustering, dist(scaled_data))
  mean(ss[, 3])
}

# Calculate average silhouette for k = 2 to k = 10
avg_sil_values <- map_dbl(2:10, ~ avg_sil(.x, scaled_data))

# Plot average silhouette width
plot(2:10, avg_sil_values, type = "b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
     xlab = "Number of clusters K", ylab = "Average Silhouette Width")

HIERARCHICAL CLUSTERINGS

#define linkage methods
m <- c( "average", "single", "complete", "ward")
names(m) <- c( "average", "single", "complete", "ward")

#function to compute agglomerative coefficient
ac <- function(x) {
  agnes(scaled_data, method = x)$ac
}

#calculate agglomerative coefficient for each clustering linkage method
sapply(m, ac)
##   average    single  complete      ward 
## 0.5337248 0.3675819 0.6231460 0.7437755
# Perform hierarchical clustering using Ward's minimum variance
clust <- agnes(scaled_data, method = "ward")

# Produce dendrogram
pltree(clust, cex = 0.6, hang = -1, main = "Dendrogram")

# Cut the dendrogram into 2 clusters
groups <- cutree(clust, k=2)

# Find number of observations in each cluster
table(groups)
## groups
##  1  2 
##  8 10
# Append cluster labels to original data
fixed_data <- cbind(merged_final, cluster = groups)

# Merge final_data with italy_geo
fixed_data <- merge(fixed_data, italy_geo, by = "Territory")

#display first six rows of final data

RIDGE REGRESSION (addressing Multicollinearity and Outliers)

# Define predictor and response variables
y <- scaled_data$Monthly_housing_euro
x <- as.matrix(scaled_data[, c('GDP_euro', 
                               'Employment_rate',
                               'Mental_rate_per_100people', 
                               'Total_enroll', 
                               'Average_annual_salary_euro',
                               'Violent_crimes_per_10000_people',
                               'Museum_density_per_100km2',
                               'Park_density_per_100km2',
                               'Non_Eu_resident_permit_1stGenuary',
                               'Life_expectancy_in_years',
                               'Childhood_services_benefited_percentage',
                               'Rural_tourism_facilities_per100km2',
                               'Renewable_electricity_percentage',
                               'Highcared_hospital_per10000people')])

# Fit ridge regression model
ridge_model <- glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0)

# Summary of the ridge regression model
summary(ridge_model)
##           Length Class     Mode   
## a0         100   -none-    numeric
## beta      1400   dgCMatrix S4     
## df         100   -none-    numeric
## dim          2   -none-    numeric
## lambda     100   -none-    numeric
## dev.ratio  100   -none-    numeric
## nulldev      1   -none-    numeric
## npasses      1   -none-    numeric
## jerr         1   -none-    numeric
## offset       1   -none-    logical
## call         4   -none-    call   
## nobs         1   -none-    numeric
# Perform k-fold cross-validation to find the optimal lambda value
cv_model <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0)
## Warning: Option grouped=FALSE enforced in cv.glmnet, since < 3 observations per
## fold
# Plot cross-validated mean squared error (CV-MSE) vs. log(lambda)
plot(cv_model)

# Find the optimal lambda value that minimizes test MSE
best_lambda <- cv_model$lambda.min
print(paste("Optimal lambda value:", best_lambda))
## [1] "Optimal lambda value: 0.206093061166557"
# Produce Ridge trace plot
plot(ridge_model, xvar = "lambda")

# Find coefficients of the best model
best_model <- glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, lambda = best_lambda)
coef(best_model)
## 15 x 1 sparse Matrix of class "dgCMatrix"
##                                                    s0
## (Intercept)                             -6.548140e-16
## GDP_euro                                 8.549355e-02
## Employment_rate                          2.328712e-01
## Mental_rate_per_100people                4.013725e-02
## Total_enroll                             9.720672e-02
## Average_annual_salary_euro               2.868945e-01
## Violent_crimes_per_10000_people          2.264344e-01
## Museum_density_per_100km2               -6.033744e-02
## Park_density_per_100km2                  1.635823e-01
## Non_Eu_resident_permit_1stGenuary        8.136465e-02
## Life_expectancy_in_years                -9.969069e-02
## Childhood_services_benefited_percentage  2.690649e-02
## Rural_tourism_facilities_per100km2       2.376228e-02
## Renewable_electricity_percentage        -1.922333e-01
## Highcared_hospital_per10000people       -1.462110e-02
# Calculate R-squared of the model on training data
y_predicted <- predict(ridge_model, s = best_lambda, newx = x)

# Calculate Sum of Squares Total (SST) and Sum of Squares Error (SSE)
sst <- sum((y - mean(y))^2)
sse <- sum((y_predicted - y)^2)

# Calculate R-squared
rsq <- 1 - sse / sst
print(paste("R-squared:", rsq))
## [1] "R-squared: 0.958995497256194"
